  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 땅에 쓰여져 : '
    value: “하늘에 쓰이는 데는 용(龍)이 제일이고, 땅에 쓰이는 데는 말[馬]이 제일이다[天用莫如龍 地用莫如馬].” 하였다. 《사기》
  - key: '[주-D002] 기린각(麒麟閣)ㆍ능연각(凌烟閣) : '
    value: 기린각에는 한 선제(漢宣帝)가 공신 곽광(霍光)ㆍ장안세(張安世) 등 14명의 화상을 그려두었고, 능연각에는 당 태종(唐太宗)이 공신 장손무기(長孫無忌)ㆍ두여회(杜如晦)ㆍ위징(魏徵) 등 12명의 화상을 그려 두었다.
  - key: '[주-D003] 말똥구리가 …… 듯이 : '
    value: 자기 힘을 헤아리지 못하고 강적을 대항함이 마치 말똥구리가 성난 팔로 수레바퀴를 막음과 같다는 말이다.
  - key: '[주-D004] 사특한 것들 : '
    value: 이성계가 위화도에서 회군하여 폐한 우왕(禑王) 및 죽인 최영(崔瑩) 등을 뜻한다.
  - key: '[주-D005] 용의 …… 붙어 : '
    value: 처음 창업(創業)하는 제왕(帝王)에게 붙어서 부귀(富貴)를 구하는 것을 말한다.
  - key: '[주-D006] 벽돌을 나름 : '
    value: 도간(陶侃)이 광주자사(廣州刺史)로 있으면서 일이 없을 때 아침마다 벽돌 백 개를 서재 밖으로 나르고 저녁에는 날라 들여오곤 했는데, 사람이 그 까닭을 물으니, “내가 바야흐로 힘을 중원(中原)에 쓰는데, 너무 편안하여 일을 감당치 못할까 걱정되기 때문이다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D007] 변(變)이 재갈에 나기도 : '
    value: 말이 달리다가 엎어지는 것을 보고 재갈[銜橛]의 변이라 한다.
  - key: '[주-D008] 길짐승은 …… 두고 : '
    value: “새는 날아 고향으로 돌아가고, 토끼는 뛰어 굴로 돌아가며, 여우는 죽을 때 언덕으로 머리 둔다[狐死首丘].” 《회남자(淮南子)》 설림(說林) 본래 고향을 지향하는 뜻이나, 여기서는 그저 ‘죽다’의 뜻이다.
  - key: '[주-D009] 썩은 밧줄 : '
    value: 《서경》에 “내가 만백성에 임함에 송구함이 썩은 밧줄로 여섯 말[馬]을 제어함 같다[予臨非民 懍乎若朽索之馭六馬].” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D010] 소금 수레에 …… 당하고 : '
    value: 높은 재주, 큰 인물이 때를 만나지 못하여 천한 역(役)에 종사한다는 말이다. 가의(賈誼)의 〈조굴원부(吊屈原賦)〉에 “천리마가 두 귀를 늘어뜨리고 소금수레를 끌도다[驥垂兩耳兮服鹽車].”라 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D011] 의장(儀仗)에 …… 섰더라도 : '
    value: 의장에 늘어선 말은 종일 소리 없이 있으면 콩 곡식을 배불리 먹되, 한 번 소리 내어 울면 쫓겨난다.
  - key: '[주-D001] 遣 : '
    value: 遺
english:
  title: Ode to the Eight Divine Steeds
  author: Shin Suk-ju
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I have heard that our dynasty took root in the northern lands, and three sage rulers passed down the legacy of loyalty and virtue, their might and merit growing ever brighter. In those days, the Goryeo kingdom was in its twilight, mired in chaos and decay. Yet Heaven watched over the East and brought forth our Progenitor, the Great King Tae-jo, who secured the ancestral enterprise with heart set on rescue and renewal. Undaunted, he marched forward.

    In the twenty-second year of Zhizheng, in spring of the year Renyin, he swept away the Red Bandits. That autumn, he drove back the Nakhchous to the east. In the third year of Hongwu, he purged Yuan remnants at Dongning. In the tenth year, he defeated the Japanese pirates at Jirisan. That autumn, he fought at Dongjing. In the thirteenth year, battle at Inyuol. In the eighteenth year, combat at Tutong. In the twenty-first year, he turned back at Wihwado with righteous resolve. Through twenty-seven years of warfare, hundreds upon hundreds of battles were fought, ten thousand perils overcome, until the scourge was erased and the people rescued from ruin. Heaven's Mandate and the people's hearts converged upon the true ruler, and thus our great enterprise was established, its blessings flowing to all ages. Yet the merit in crushing our foes and clarifying our realm was won upon horseback. Such service of horses cannot fade from memory—it deserves to endure forever.

    Among them, eight steeds were most noble and most glorious in deed. Now our Sovereign has ordered these eight portrayed and praised, that their legend might be preserved for ages. Thus does he honor his forebears, ensuring vigilance against complacency, and impart to his heirs the teaching that the victories our ancestors won through hardship must never be forgotten. If our saintly descendants, mindful of how the preceding dynasty lost its realm so easily and how our ancestors won it through such travail, never forget the service of these eight divine steeds, then shall our Eastern realm enjoy endless blessing through ten thousand ages. Your servant, though humble in station, has witnessed this great enterprise and honors it with song. I reverently bow and present this ode:

    When a sage sits in authority,
    He cultivates virtue with careful reverence.
    Through thirty years of governance,
    Culture and teaching shine resplendent.
    On all four borders, no alarm;
    Court and realm rest in tranquil peace.
    Hence we learn how hard it is to preserve what is gained,
    And how poison lurks in ease and comfort.
    Looking back on the trials of founding,
    We proclaim the righteousness of our great forebear.
    Even the eight steeds, though humble in appearance,
    Were deemed worthy of honor and remembrance.

    When divine steeds are born—
    How miraculous! How wondrous!
    They receive celestial essence,
    As dragons beget sacred spawn.
    Vast and boundless their power,
    Serpentine and flowing their forms.
    The vital breath swirls and spirals,
    Light and shadow interweave.
    Winds and rains transform at their pleasure,
    Yin and yang open and close at their command.
    All beauty merges in perfect harmony,
    Forming these transcendent creatures of heaven.

    Steady and graceful they stand,
    Sleek and magnificent of form.
    Ears sharpen like splitting bamboo,
    Hooves strike like scattered hail.
    Square steps follow perfect measure,
    Round turns follow the compass.
    Their frames gleam with lustrous beauty—
    Waving manes, flowing tails,
    Proud and prancing they stride,
    Swift and soaring they leap.
    When they gallop, lightning turns back,
    When they thunder, divine light scatters.
    As they charge, cool breezes blow;
    As they twist, spring clouds rise.
    One whinny—the western sands grow still;
    Twice they call—the northern winds surrender.
    Such steeds come once in a thousand years,
    Worthy to stand beside unicorn and phoenix.

    When divine steeds are used—
    How supreme! How mighty!
    On earth, where all things find their purpose,
    They meet their destined hour.
    They gallop and surge with boundless power,
    They stand alone in their nobility.
    Like wind-driven dust they fly,
    Their hooves outpacing thought,
    Their shadows unable to keep pace.
    They labor in formation yet never tire,
    They serve in bridle and harness,
    Yet bearing heavy burdens, journeying far,
    Their strength seems never fully taxed.
    United with man in single purpose,
    They accomplish deeds of wonder.
    Their names fly forth, their fame spreads wide,
    Their deeds fixed forever in paint,
    During endless ages remaining undiminished,
    Their fragrance drifting through ten thousand years.

    Such steeds come once in a hundred ages—
    Rare beyond measure, worthy to stand with Kirin Pavilion and Lingyan Gallery.

    Oh, that divine steeds are born—miraculous, wondrous beyond words!
    Oh, that divine steeds are used—supreme, mighty beyond recording!
    This is why Heaven produces such sacred beings, displaying such marvels to the world, appearing but once in a thousand years, gracing our Korean realm as the supreme auspice of our Mandate received.

    Consider those dark days: the Golden Cock expired, the Crimson Deer was lost. The great wheel of fortune departed; the nation's pulse grew faint. Heaven's net was torn asunder; the Eastern lands sank into chaos. Treacherous ministers flourished within; brigands raged without on all sides. Northern winds howled, driving sand; the dark waters churned and heaved. The drums of war thundered relentlessly; bells and gongs clanged everywhere. Creatures gnawed and snapped at one another. The earth ran red with blood like rivers; white bones piled high like mountains. Homes became ash and ember; villages transformed into battlefields. Border regions lay in ruin; the Middle Kingdom turned to wilderness. Thus was the world's disorder absolute, the people's suffering extreme. Without a sage, who could save us from drowning?

    Then came our Progenitor, fortune's instrument for this crucial hour, blessed with nature's highest gifts, endowed by Heaven with courage and wisdom. Moved by the people's innocent suffering, he rose to reclaim the legacy of four generations. He answered the pole star's movement and turned Heaven's axis, rotating the firmament itself. He unfurled his martial prowess, commanding wind and thunder as his servants. Where his banner pointed, all crumbled like rotten wood.

    The Red Bandits charged like wild boars, destroying walled cities, devastating settlements. They plundered and burned with savage fury, the ancestral shrines consumed in flame, the royal court scattered in flight. Yet our great forebear, displaying courage and raising his banner, led the van with drawn bow, wielded his personal guard as bait. The villainous hordes trampled one another; ten thousand fell. His sword flashed as he leaped from his steed, scaling walls in pursuit. The brigands were driven back and defeated.

    The Nakhchous, cunning and fierce, allied with border traitors to ravage the frontier people. They advanced steadily toward Hong-won, their power growing fierce, their intent to swallow us whole. Yet our great forebear, reading events with wisdom, rode forth alone, severed enemy commanders, captured their flags. Arrows found mouth and armpit; whiskers were plucked like dry branches. Repeatedly defeated, the enemy shrank and fled, desperate and gasping. Their cunning master lost all resolve and became loyal forever.

    Far away lay Dongning, the remnant of fallen Yuan, with its high peaks and narrow passes. The Yalu River churned between north and south. The Goryeo king commanded our forebear to reclaim these distant lands. Our ancestral general set forth, his martial spirit shaking heaven. Purple mist gathered in the sky; fortune's signs appeared. When brigands offered token resistance, they surrendered at the sight of our banner. The stubborn chieftain, clinging to misguided loyalty, still defended Olli Fortress.

    Olli Fortress stood sheer and heaven-carved, its cliffs towering and grim. Yet our forebear's sacred might blazed forth. The isolated city crumbled from within; surrender came from all quarters, as moths rush toward flame. Benevolent authority reached far; we purified the northern wastes.

    Across the eastern sea lay the pirate stronghold, where island barbarians, born to boats, grew savage and swift. They pursued profit as if courting death, committing petty thievery, slipping through our coastal gaps. Their sails blackened the sea; their ships wove like weavers' looms. The king commanded our forebear to strike swiftly. The pirate horde gathered at Jirisan's flank. Our martial might soared—a single arrow stole their courage. Defeated and scattered, they fled to high ground. Sheer cliffs and rushing combat—blade and spear rained down. Our forebear's charge blazed white-hot; purple lightning cut across the sun. The divine steed surged upward a thousand feet in a single leap. At its touch, the foe tumbled and fell, filling valleys with corpses. Like mountains crushing eggs, nothing escaped.

    The island barbarians, unrepentant, struck at the southwest. Fortifications fell like empty air; defenders were cut down like grass. Whole provinces burned. In their fury at Dongjing, many generals lost heart and fled before engagement. Yet our forebear received command and rode forth. When he fired seventeen arrows, each felled a foe with a shot through the left eye. The enemy scattered, trampling each other. Our forebear dismounted, called for wine and music. Surviving brigands fled to safety. As their forces grew desperate and desperate, arrows fell like rain. Yet his spirit remained unmoved—he calmly issued orders, and his subordinates destroyed the remaining enemy.

    The island barbarians, unrepentant still, invaded the south. With no time to defend heights or preserve cities, they overwhelmed and burned like sweeping through an empty land. They ravaged to Yunbong itself. Our forebear, receiving command and swearing to exterminate the villains, poured forth such sincerity that white rainbows appeared. A thousand li lay strewn with corpses piled like mountains. Our forebear, moved with compassion, ceased to eat and sleep. He mobilized the generals and fought at Inyuol, displaying might and martial valor, leading his troops in person. He penetrated their formations and scattered their ranks, toppling a notorious general. Blades snapped and bent; none dared resist. The nation rejoiced to welcome his triumphant return.

    The island barbarians, unrepentant, struck at Hamheung and Hongwon. They charged like whales and snapped like mad dogs. Generals lost courage and fled without battle, as lambs before tigers. The king commanded our forebear to lead the campaign. He consulted seven arrows to divine victory—the army erupted in cheers. He studied the terrain, set hidden ambush, loosened his reins and advanced slowly. When the war horn sounded, the enemy's courage broke. Like fish in a cauldron they gathered, scattering in panic. Our forebear sat at ease, showing no urgency; he loosened his saddle and called them forth. Battle raged in circling engagements. All four ambushes rose at once—the enemy fell into our net like caged birds. They crashed and trampled one another. Thus the shores and highlands became our own.

    Heavens' Mandate was changing. Fate seized the usurper's will. The foolish youth could not reckon his weakness and dared attack the Great Realm. In the sixth month, he raised armies pointing eastward toward Liaodong. Court officials trembled; the people grew anxious. Though urgent warnings came, deaf ears ignored them. Stranded on a lonely island as great rains fell, armies stood trapped between advance and retreat—all grew fearful and weak.

    Yet our forebear raised the banner of righteousness. From white feathers and crimson bow, ten thousand voices sang as one—not through planning but through unified will. Even distant Jurchen tribes followed a thousand leagues. Old and young joined hands; people brought provisions to welcome him. Evil was purged without market-place alarm. Disorder was quelled and rightness restored; weapons were sheathed and warfare ceased. Through this, the realm found stability and the people found peace.

    All these deeds were wrought by our Great Progenitor's towering merit and lofty virtue, triumphantly achieved. Deep favor and abundant blessing soaked into all living beings. Blessings were planted and virtue sown deep, their roots running deep and sources far, becoming the foundation upon which countless generations of descendants would stand.

    Yet these are but the outline. Other victories like Dalcheon's triumph, Cheolgwan's success, Haepung's battles, Liaoyang's fall—countless great and small engagements, all victorious wherever fought. Though born of our forebear's sage strategy and divine prowess, how could this exceed human capacity? In those days, brave warriors and wise counselors, each with some skill or talent, strove to display their abilities. They grasped the dragon's scales and clung to the phoenix's wings, hurrying before and after, clustering and streaming, moving left and right in cooperation—all contributing to great achievement.

    For Heaven, when it sends a sage to rescue an age of crisis, must also send heroes and champions to follow him. And it must send auspicious omens and sacred beings to aid their purpose. Thus the birth of these eight divine steeds was Heaven's design—all meant to aid our Great Progenitor's rise.

    When two armies met in combat, war drums roared and thunder rolled. The killing essence pierced heaven; battle clouds rose in layers. Cunning tactics and swift changes contested for opportunity and advantage. Mighty warriors and fierce champions—bearing down like bears, slashing like tigers—white blades gleaming frostlike, arrows falling like rain. Confusion boiled and churned; clouds gathered and lightning burst. Countless soldiers pressed and swayed. Victory hung upon a moment's turn; life and death decided in a breath.

    Our majestic Progenitor, like a falcon, unleashed his power. He struck here and there where resistance crumbled. Lightning and thunder erupted; fire poured forth like whip-strikes. Ten thousand men gave way, and he moved as he pleased. Swift and nimble, mists scattered and smoke cleared—harsh frost scattered leaves; raging fire consumed hair. Whatever faced him shattered; whatever touched him crumbled. Bamboo split by a cutting wave could not match his momentum; a rolling stone could not match his fury.

    One endowed with extraordinary gifts receives extraordinary mandate. One who accomplishes deeds beyond precedent enjoys blessings beyond measure. Our Great Progenitor met an age of chaos armed with Heaven-given sagacity. His efforts were supreme; his achievements unrivaled. His authority commanded respect; his merit exceeded all reward. Where Heaven's Mandate turned, human hearts followed. Thus he answered Heaven and satisfied the people, transformed the family inheritance into a nation, extended his generation's remaining blessings that flow through ten thousand ages without ceasing.

    Yet his martial skill was honed through discipline. He trained continually, not idling but exercising. At leisure, he hunted across vast territories—not merely for sport, but to traverse forests and hills. Where mountains and plains rose and fell in succession, where ridges linked and connected, where swamps lay sunken and valleys descended to abysses, where stone walls stood heaven-carved and sheer cliffs hung suspended—places where wild beasts sheltered and human feet could not tread.

    There our great forebear rode forth and back, commanding his steed: forward and it advanced; backward and it retreated. Its circles were measured, its turnings precise. Star-swift it arrived; wheel-quick it turned and flashed. Arrows never strayed; where aimed, they pierced the eye. Wild beasts fell to earth and birds tumbled from sky.

    Masters of chariot-craft like Wang Liang and Zao Fu, mighty strongmen like Ben and Yu, all surrendered and gasped in awe. This was the sage's sacred prowess—yet also the divine steed's mighty achievement.

    When sheer cliffs and treacherous quagmires threatened in sudden crisis, when no mere strategist or general could employ their craft—then did the divine steed's support of our Progenitor exceed what mortal effort could achieve. This is why our Sovereign had these eight steeds captured in paint and their sacred deeds recorded on lasting bone—preserving filial devotion toward beasts his forebear cherished, extending wise instruction to his heirs, placing exhortations beside his seat, and keeping urgent warnings bound to fraying rope.

    Behold the new painting—as if Heaven itself descended and unfurled it! Its light shines suddenly; frost and wind move the silk; creation animates the brush. It raises dusty forms from earth's depths, elevating them to presently awe us.

    Their shapes shimmer; their presence surges with power. They cross clouds and chase wind, flash lightning and congeal frost. Unicorns play and dragons leap; leopards gleam black and lions shine gold. Layered brilliance and piled silks, massed jade and linked pearls. In different forms they share one function, gathering auspice and spreading good omen. Awesome dignity blazes; fierce radiance shines bright.

    War-scarred from a hundred battles, fragments of arrows still embedded, the very attitude of their charging assault appears as if from yesterday. Their martial spirit appalls all viewers; their terror chills blood and raises hair, freezing even the soul—taking days to settle. Yet these are but the mere dregs of the eight steeds! If mere paintings can so move our sight and hearing, imagine the actual creatures of that era—separated by a thousand years, yet rising respect across the ages. Such is the ultimate nature of sacred beings that proves difficult even for humans.

    Why should one require living flesh and mirrored shadow to call it extraordinary?

    Alas! All creatures have their encounters; each encounter has its time. If a steed is born without meeting its hour, a salt cart could trap it in toil. If its encounter lacks proper season, even ceremonial service leaves it meaningless, though standing in grand procession it gains only beans to eat and never a single whinny of freedom.

    Yet these eight steeds—they were born in our Progenitor's dragon-rising age and died under our Sovereign's remembrance. They achieved time and encounter, gained purpose and trust. May they endure through endless ages without regret.

    The ode concludes. I then composed this song:

    If a dragon's son appears, a divine steed comes,
    Sent forth by Heaven itself.
    Wind and cloud scatter; thunder and rain race—
    If a noble steed appears, the dragon's companion,
    Born with sacred nature, dead with eternal fame—
    If a noble steed appears, the dragon's very essence,
    Their name unchanged through ten thousand ages—
    If a noble steed appears, the dragon's very form.
